Bay-Area Bikeshare Data Exploration¶

Author : James Funware West¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. The data can be gotten from the sources below :

  • Website: http://www.bayareabikeshare.com/
  • Systems Data Page: http://www.bayareabikeshare.com/open-data
  • Data being shared: Trip, Station, Membership, Weather, Bike and Dock Availability

This data is only for the month of February, 2019.

The purpose of this analysis is the understand the behaviour of our users, and point key factors that influence how they use our services. This analysis will focus on usertypes to understand how different factors like time of the day, day of the week, age, gender affects the duration of user's trip and how often they use the service.

Some of the questions we will be answering are as follows :

  • What is the gender proportion of users ?
  • What is the proportion of usertypes ?
  • What is the age distribution of users ?
  • What is the distribution of duration of trips ?
  • How long does different usertypes ride ?
  • When do different usertypes ride ?
  • Why do different usertypes use the service ?

Data Issues¶

  • start_time and end_time have datatype as object instead of datetime
  • member_birth_year is saved as a float , should be changed to int or dt.year
  • Some columns are not needed for our analysis
  • Convert duration_sec to minutes and rename column as duration_min
  • Add a weekday column
  • Add a new column time_period indicating time of the day (i.e morning, afternoon, evening)
  • Add a new column indicating the age of the customer

We are interested in finding features that affect trip duration and number of trips

6. Add time_period column¶

Add a column stating time periods: Morning, afternoon, evening

In [43]:
#create a function for the new column creation
def timep(x):
    if x.hour <= 12:
        return 'Morning'
    elif x.hour > 12 and x.hour <= 16:
        return 'Afternoon'
    else:
        return 'Evening'
In [44]:
# Apply the function
df_clean['time_period'] = df_clean['start_time'].apply(timep)

Exploration¶

Let's make some functions to reduce repititive codes.

In [56]:
# function to create a figure of boxplot and violin plots
def bvp(x, y,title):
    col = sns.color_palette()[0]
    plt.figure(figsize=[20,8])
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    sns.boxplot(data = df_clean, x = x, y = y, color = col)
    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    sns.violinplot(data = df_clean, x = x, y = y, color = col)
    plt.suptitle(title, fontsize = 20);
In [57]:
# function for univariate countplots
def ucp(x,title):
    plt.figure(figsize=[10,5])
    col = sns.color_palette()[0]
    sns.countplot(data = df_clean, x= x, color = col)
    plt.title(title, fontsize = 20);


# function for bivariate countplots
def bcp(x,hue,title):
    plt.figure(figsize=[10,5])
    sns.countplot(data = df_clean, x = x,hue=hue)
    plt.title(title, fontsize = 20);

Conclusions¶

After analysis, the following findings were recorded:

  1. There is no distinct difference in behaviour between genders recorded in the dataset, although female users recorded longer trip duration compared to other genders.

  2. Majority of the users are male users, and over 90% of users are subscribers.

  3. Most users are around the age of 25 - 45.

  4. The bikeshare service records a lot of trips during the week and less trips during weekends.

  5. Majority of the trips are started in the rush hour of the morning and the evening, this shows that a great percentage of users use the service for transit to work.

  6. The behaviour of subscribers remains constant all through the week in terms of trip duration and only slightly increases on weekends. Meanwhile, customers record longer trips during weekends.

  7. Customers use the service for leisure.
